When you talk about very good to find, what are you talking about?
Well, the conditions of books are very important to anybody who collects.
Booksellers should be very conservative in the way they define their books.
A book is mint as new when it comes off the printing press.
Mint means
As new?
Yeah, I would say mint means as new.
Fine means that the book is exactly like mint except you looked at it, you breathed on it, or you touched it.
That means it's actually been handled.
A book in fine condition should not have any defect whatsoever.
A book in very good condition can have minor defects, but they should not in any way impair the integrity of the book or the dust wrapper.
Well, what's near fine, then, which you see all the time?
What's near fine?
That's somebody's wish that it was fine, but can't make it fine, so it has to come up with an alternative.
One of the greatest things about book collecting is reading catalogs.
A very quick story.

I once had a book which had its front cover detached, its spine was missing, its back pages were missing, somebody Crayola'd five of the pages, pages 13 through 17 were missing, and there was a ring from water stained on the front cover, and the dealer said, otherwise, fine.
So be careful when you're reading them catalogs.
Okay.

just wondering if it was worth anything.

Unfortunately, Matthew Arnold falls into that category of great authors who were once collectible who no longer have maintained their value.
It's one of the things that you have to be very conscious of if you become a book collector and you really are collecting for value or you want to invest money.

There are a lot of catalogs which will show Matthew Arnold and other authors at a specifically high price, but quite frankly, those market prices have dropped because nobody's no longer interested in them.
for collecting.

How many of them ever come back into fashion?
Well, I don't know if it's like peg-legged pants or what kind of analogy you make on it.
I mean, occasionally an author will become popular.
I'm not saying Jane Austen has ever gone out of vogue, but with all the movies that came out, there's an interest in Jane Austen for first again.
I don't think that's really a good point.
I was thinking somebody like Edmund Burke, for example.
Nobody read him for a century, and then we heard more and more talk about conservatism politically, and all of a sudden, people are writing biographies and writing about Edmund Burke.
Right, and so, you know, so an Edward Burke-Tratisse is now worth some money.
I'm trying to think of somebody else.
Anthony Trollope.
Anthony Trollope became very popular again when they started doing PBS specials.
I mean, his books really never decreased, decreased in value, but boy, now...
There was a period when Anthony Trollope went up the ladder overnight.
I mean, books that were selling for $100 were now selling for $500.
So, you know, a lot of this has to do with the fact that as movies are adapted or, you know, television takes shows.
I mean, we've seen this with John Gresham.
We've seen it with Forrest Gump.
He's a perfect example.
Oh, sure.
Yeah, I mean, that's a book that couldn't sell for a dollar, but now it's a $400 book.
Okay, who knows who the next popular author is going to be?
But you have pointed out to me the amazing thing.
For example, every week it seems like somebody's making a miniseries of Sidney Shelton, but his books never seem to appreciate in value.
Why is that?
Because I don't think the book collecting world accepts the fact that he's a quality author.
I'm not going to say anything on either side, but there are some authors that just will never be accepted for being valued as literature.
They might be valued as screenplays or TV, but they are never going to make the transition to the literature world, literary world.
